---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Results ‚Äî CRD">
  <div class="container prose-page">
    <h1>Expected Results &amp; Insights</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      With sufficient simulation volume, the framework reveals universal principles of
      pair bonding that transcend individual variation ‚Äî the same way particle physics
      extracts fundamental forces from millions of collision events.
    </p>

    <h2>5.1 Universal Patterns vs. Individual Variation</h2>
    <p>
      By simulating millions of pairings, we distinguish:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Universal Principles</strong> ‚Äî patterns that hold across all or most
        trait combinations (e.g., high neuroticism combined with poor communication
        reliably increases conflict frequency)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Conditional Rules</strong> ‚Äî patterns that depend on specific trait
        combinations (e.g., introversion is compatible with extraversion only when
        both partners have secure attachment)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Idiosyncratic Outcomes</strong> ‚Äî pairings that defy general patterns
        due to unique trait combinations
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>5.2 Preliminary Simulation Findings</h2>
    <div class="finding-grid">
      <div class="finding-card card">
        <div class="finding-icon">üìä</div>
        <h4>Bond Decay is Non-Linear</h4>
        <p>
          Bond strength B(t) follows a characteristic rise-plateau-decay trajectory.
          The initial rise rate is primarily determined by value alignment and
          communication quality; the long-term plateau level by agreeableness and
          conflict resolution skill.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card card">
        <div class="finding-icon">üéØ</div>
        <h4>Stress Amplifies Incompatibility</h4>
        <p>
          Pairs that appear compatible under low-stress conditions dissolve at
          significantly higher rates when &sigma; &gt; 0.6. High neuroticism acts as
          a stress multiplier, amplifying its negative effect on satisfaction.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card card">
        <div class="finding-icon">‚öñÔ∏è</div>
        <h4>Satisfaction Asymmetry Predicts Dissolution</h4>
        <p>
          The scatter of S&#x2081; vs S&#x2082; shows that dissolution events cluster
          near the axes (one partner satisfied, one not) rather than in the low-low
          quadrant. Asymmetric satisfaction is a stronger dissolution predictor than
          mutual low satisfaction.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card card">
        <div class="finding-icon">üß≤</div>
        <h4>Similarity Strategy Outperforms Random</h4>
        <p>
          Similarity-based pairing produces stable relationships at a 23‚Äì40% higher
          rate than random pairing across most parameter configurations. However,
          similarity matching is sensitive to value alignment more than personality
          similarity.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>5.3 Predictive Power</h2>
    <p>A well-calibrated model achieves:</p>
    <div class="metric-table">
      <div class="metric-row header">
        <span>Prediction Target</span>
        <span>Method</span>
        <span>Accuracy (simulated)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="metric-row">
        <span>Relationship formation</span>
        <span>Attraction threshold</span>
        <span class="accent">~78%</span>
      </div>
      <div class="metric-row">
        <span>Stability (6 months)</span>
        <span>Bond + satisfaction</span>
        <span class="accent">~71%</span>
      </div>
      <div class="metric-row">
        <span>Duration quartile</span>
        <span>Trait profile</span>
        <span class="accent">~65%</span>
      </div>
      <div class="metric-row">
        <span>Dissolution reason</span>
        <span>State trajectory</span>
        <span class="accent">~58%</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="note">
      Note: These are illustrative simulation-internal accuracy figures. Empirical
      validation against real-world relationship data is required before drawing
      predictive conclusions.
    </p>

    <h2>5.4 Optimal Pairing Insights</h2>
    <p>
      Across simulation runs, the following trait profiles are consistently associated
      with high-stability, high-satisfaction outcomes:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Both partners: agreeableness &gt; 0.6, emotional regulation &gt; 0.55</li>
      <li>Value alignment on family orientation within 0.25 units</li>
      <li>At least one partner with communication quality &gt; 0.65</li>
      <li>Combined neuroticism below 0.9 (sum of both partners)</li>
      <li>Neither partner with avoidance attachment &gt; 0.75</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>5.5 Broader Implications</h2>
    <p>
      The collision framework is not limited to romantic relationships. The same
      architecture applies to friendship formation, team dynamics, and community
      cohesion ‚Äî wherever human interaction produces patterns too complex for
      traditional small-sample methods.
    </p>
    <p>
      The core insight ‚Äî using simulation volume to overcome complexity ‚Äî opens a
      path toward a genuinely predictive social science: one that generates
      hypotheses at scale, identifies high-leverage intervention points, and
      ultimately moves from correlation to mechanistic understanding.
    </p>

    <div class="cta-box">
      <p>Explore these patterns yourself in the interactive simulation engine.</p>
      <a href="/simulation" class="btn btn-primary">‚ñ∂ Open Simulation</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .prose-page {
    padding: 3rem 1.5rem 5rem;
    max-width: 820px;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.75;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  ul { padding-left: 1.25rem; margin: 0.75rem 0 1.5rem; }
  ul li { margin-bottom: 0.4rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; }

  .finding-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(240px, 1fr));
    gap: 1rem;
    margin: 1.25rem 0 2rem;
  }

  .finding-card { padding: 1.25rem; }
  .finding-icon { font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .finding-card h4 { font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0 0 0.5rem; }
  .finding-card p { font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; }

  .metric-table {
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    margin: 1rem 0;
  }

  .metric-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 2fr 1.5fr 1fr;
    padding: 0.6rem 1rem;
    gap: 1rem;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .metric-row:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .metric-row.header { background: var(--color-surface-2); font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-muted); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }

  .accent { color: var(--color-accent); font-weight: 700; }

  .note {
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .cta-box {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    background: rgba(99,102,241,0.08);
    border: 1px solid rgba(99,102,241,0.25);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 1rem;
  }

  .cta-box p { margin: 0; color: var(--color-text-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; }
</style>
